One way to skip the first instance of the root joint and go straight to its children while maintaining the recursive function's proper working is to add a conditional statement at the beginning of the function that checks whether the current joint is the root joint. If it is the root joint, then you can skip over it and directly process its children. Here's an example code snippet:

```
void processJoint(Joint* joint) {
  if (joint == rootJoint) { // root joint has no animation set, skip it
    for (Joint* child : joint->children) {
      processJoint(child);
    }
    return;
  }

  // rest of the function to handle non-root joints
}
```

In this example, `rootJoint` is a pointer to the root joint of the hierarchy. The first conditional statement checks if the current joint is equal to `rootJoint`. If it is, then the function skips over the rest of the code and directly processes the children of the root joint. This way, the function will skip the root joint and start processing at its children. If the current joint is not the root joint, the function continues normally and processes the joint and its children.

Yes, you can skip any bones that don't have animations in a similar manner to the root joint. During the recursion, when you encounter a bone that doesn't have an animation, you can skip it and move on to its children. Here's an example code snippet:

```
void processJoint(Joint* joint, glm::mat4 parentTransform) {
  glm::mat4 currentTransform = parentTransform * joint->localTransform;
  if (joint->animator == NULL) {
    for (auto child : joint->children) {
      processJoint(child, currentTransform);
    }
    return;
  }
  // rest of the function to handle animated joints
}
```

In this example, the `animator` member indicates whether the joint has an animation or not. If it is null, it means the joint doesn't have an animation. The function checks whether the current joint has an animator or not. If it doesn't, it skips over it and goes on to process its children. The current transform matrix is still updated by multiplying the parent transform with the local transform of the current joint. 

This approach ensures that any non-animated bones are skipped, and only the animated bones are processed. It also ensures that the transform hierarchy is correctly applied to the model.

Yes, it is possible to return to the next child higher up in the hierarchy after processing a joint's children in a recursive function. You can achieve this by using the call stack to keep track of the parent joints.

In a recursive function, each function call creates a new stack frame, which contains all the local variables for that function call. When a function call completes, the stack frame is popped off the call stack, and the program returns to the previous function call.

To return to the next child higher up in the hierarchy, you can simply return from the current function call once you have finished processing all the children of the current joint. This will pop the current stack frame off the call stack and return to the previous function call. The previous function call will then continue processing the parent joint's next child (if there are any).

Here's an example code snippet:

```
void processJoint(Joint* joint, glm::mat4 parentTransform) {
  glm::mat4 currentTransform = parentTransform * joint->localTransform;

  // process current joint's children
  for (auto child : joint->children) {
    processJoint(child, currentTransform);
  }

  // return to parent joint
  return;
}
```

In this example, the function recursively calls itself for each child of the current joint. Once it has finished processing all the children, it simply returns to the previous function call, which will continue processing the parent joint's next child (if there are any).

By using the call stack to keep track of the parent joints, you can process the entire joint hierarchy in a recursive function without having to manually keep track of which joint to return to.

If your program is not returning from the function when it detects a problematic joint, it's possible that there is an issue with how you are handling the return value. 

First, you need to make sure that your function returns a value that can be checked by the calling function to ensure that an error was detected. For example, you could define your function to return a boolean value indicating whether or not an error occurred. Here's an example code snippet:

```
bool processJoint(Joint* joint, glm::mat4 parentTransform) {
  glm::mat4 currentTransform = parentTransform * joint->localTransform;

  // process joint here

  if(problemDetected) {
    return false; // return false if a problem was detected
  }

  // process current joint's children
  for (auto child : joint->children) {
    if(!processJoint(child, currentTransform)) {
        // return false immediately if a child has a problem
        return false;
    }
  }

  return true; // return true if all joints were processed successfully
}
```

In this example, the return value is set to `false` if a problem is detected in the current joint. If any child joint also has a problem, the function immediately returns `false` without processing any further joints. Finally, the function returns `true` if all joints were processed successfully.

Next, you need to make sure that the calling function properly handles the return value, and exits the function if an error is detected. Here's an example code snippet:

```
if(!processJoint(rootJoint, glm::mat4(1.0f))) {
  // handle error here (e.g. log error message, clean up resources, etc.)
  // exit the function or return an error code
}
```

In this example, the function exits or returns an error code if `processJoint` returns `false`.

By properly handling the return value of your function, you can make sure that any detected errors are properly dealt with and that the program does not continue processing and crash.

If your function is already a `void` function, you can still handle the problem by throwing an exception when a problematic joint is detected. 

When you throw an exception, it immediately stops the execution of the current function and jumps back to the caller, which can catch the exception and handle it appropriately. Here's an example code snippet:

```
void processJoint(Joint* joint, glm::mat4 parentTransform) {
  glm::mat4 currentTransform = parentTransform * joint->localTransform;

  // check if the joint is problematic
  if (isProblematic(joint)) {
    throw std::runtime_error("Problematic joint detected"); // throw exception if a problem was detected
  }

  // process joint
  ...

  // process current joint's children
  for (auto child : joint->children) {
    processJoint(child, currentTransform);
  }
}
```

In this example, the `isProblematic` function is used to check if the current joint is problematic. If it is, the function throws a `std::runtime_error` exception with an appropriate error message. 

When an exception is thrown, it is immediately propagated up the call stack to the nearest exception handler (e.g. a `try-catch` block). To handle the exception, you would use a `try-catch` block to catch the exception and handle it appropriately, like this:

```
try {
  processJoint(rootJoint, glm::mat4(1.0f));
} catch (const std::exception& e) {
  // handle error here (e.g. log error message, clean up resources, etc.)
  // exit the function or return an error code
}
```

In this example, the `try` block calls the `processJoint` function, and the `catch` block catches any `std::exception` thrown by the function. The error message can be accessed through the `e` variable, and can be used to log the error message or handle it appropriately.

By using exceptions to handle problematic joints, you can ensure that the function stops execution immediately when a problem is detected, so that any further processing is prevented.

If you want to continue processing the joint hierarchy even after a problematic joint has been detected, you can catch the exception inside the function, log the error message or handle it appropriately, and then continue processing the remaining joints. Here's an example code snippet:

```
void processJoint(Joint* joint, glm::mat4 parentTransform) {
  glm::mat4 currentTransform = parentTransform * joint->localTransform;

  try {
    // check if the joint is problematic
    if (isProblematic(joint)) {
      throw std::runtime_error("Problematic joint detected");
    }

    // process joint
    ...

    // process current joint's children
    for (auto child : joint->children) {
      processJoint(child, currentTransform);
    }
  } catch (const std::exception& e) {
