    // continue processing the remaining joints
  }
}
```

In this example, the `try` block contains the code for processing the joint and its children, similar to the previous example. However, an exception is thrown if a problematic joint is detected. 

The `catch` block catches the exception and logs the error message or handles it appropriately. The `catch` block also continues processing the remaining joints by returning from the catch block, which continues execution after the try-catch block. This way, you can continue processing the joint hierarchy even after a problematic joint has been detected.

Note that when a `try` block encounters an exception, it immediately jumps to the `catch` block, and any remaining code in the `try` block is not executed. By catching the exception inside the function, you can handle the error and continue processing the remaining joints.

Yes, you can skip processing any bone that does not have any transformations by checking for this condition in your recursive function, and then continuing to its children if it has any. If it does not have any children, you can return to the previous function call which will continue processing the remaining bones in the hierarchy.

Here's an example code snippet:

```
void processJoint(Joint* joint, glm::mat4 parentTransform) {
  glm::mat4 currentTransform = parentTransform * joint->localTransform;

  // check if the joint has any transformations
  if (hasNoTransformations(joint)) {
    if (joint->children.empty()) {
      return; // no transformations and no children, go to the next bone in the hierarchy
    } else {
      // continue with processing the children
      for (auto child : joint->children) {
        processJoint(child, currentTransform);
      }
      return;
    }
  }

  // process joint with transformations
  ...

  // process current joint's children
  for (auto child : joint->children) {
    processJoint(child, currentTransform);
  }
}
```

In this example, the `hasNoTransformations` function is called to check if the joint has any transformations. If it does not have any transformations, the function checks if the joint has any children. If it does not have any children, it returns to the previous function call. If it does have children, it continues with processing the children of the current joint by calling `processJoint` recursively. 

If the joint does have transformations, the function processes the joint, and then recursively processes its children. 

By checking for the conditions where joints have no transformations or children, you can skip processing irrelevant joints in the hierarchy and focus on those that actually have transformations.

